abstract: Mr. Schultz, the former chief executive of Starbucks, was greeted by about 40 protesters at an event after saying he would consider running for president as an independent.
snippet: Mr. Schultz, the former chief executive of Starbucks, was greeted by about 40 protesters at an event after saying he would consider running for president as an independent.
lead_paragraph: SEATTLE — As cars and pedestrians passed by during the evening rush on Thursday, Paula Harper-Christensen, a retired teacher, smiled and waved her sign with an upside-down Starbucks mermaid. “Don’t spill our chance,” the text said under the logo. Susan Glicksberg’s protest placard was more blunt: “Do Not Run!”

abstract: Of obsessions, vanity and delusions of superiority.
snippet: Of obsessions, vanity and delusions of superiority.
lead_paragraph: Why is American politics so dysfunctional? Whatever the deeper roots of our distress, the proximate cause is ideological extremism: Powerful factions are committed to false views of the world, regardless of the evidence.

headline_main: The Teachers’ Strike May Be Over, but Fights Are Simmering

abstract: A group of moderate Democrats, led by Joseph R. Biden and Michael Bloomberg, are thinking of challenging Trump. If too many centrists run, they could box each other out.
snippet: A group of moderate Democrats, led by Joseph R. Biden and Michael Bloomberg, are thinking of challenging Trump. If too many centrists run, they could box each other out.
lead_paragraph: Howard Schultz, the former Starbucks chief executive contemplating an independent run for president, stated it as a plain matter of fact: For someone with his views — a distinctly white-collar blend of conservative fiscal instincts and liberal social values — there is no suitable political party.

abstract: Mr. Garcetti would have faced a crowded field of Democratic presidential candidates, including Senator Kamala Harris of California, and long odds. No sitting mayor has ever been elected president.
snippet: Mr. Garcetti would have faced a crowded field of Democratic presidential candidates, including Senator Kamala Harris of California, and long odds. No sitting mayor has ever been elected president.
lead_paragraph: LOS ANGELES — Eric M. Garcetti, the two-term mayor of Los Angeles who has flirted with higher office the last two years by crisscrossing the country and raising money for the Democratic Party, said Tuesday he was not running for his party’s nomination for president.

headline_main: L.A. Mayor Eric Garcetti Decides Against Presidential Bid
headline_print_headline: Garcetti Won’t Throw Hat in Ring For 2020

abstract: Touring New Hampshire, Mr. Bloomberg said that it was fine to provide Medicare to uninsured Americans, but that giving it to everyone was financially untenable.
snippet: Touring New Hampshire, Mr. Bloomberg said that it was fine to provide Medicare to uninsured Americans, but that giving it to everyone was financially untenable.
lead_paragraph: A day after Senator Kamala Harris of California endorsed ending private health insurance in favor of a “Medicare for all” government plan, Michael R. Bloomberg, a possible rival of hers for the Democratic presidential nomination, said the proposal would “bankrupt us for a very long time.”

abstract: Roberto Deiaco of Armani Ristorante opens a spot in the former Da Silvano, Dell’anima reopens, and other restaurant news.
snippet: Roberto Deiaco of Armani Ristorante opens a spot in the former Da Silvano, Dell’anima reopens, and other restaurant news.
lead_paragraph: Back in 2015, when they opened their first outpost of the Ribbon, on West 72nd Street, Bruce and Eric Bromberg said their menu was designed to be replicated in other locations. Now  they’re finally testing it out. Except for a larger selection of seafood platters and a fried chicken that’s served daily instead of weekly, the 300-seat version of the Ribbon in Times Square, in the multilevel sprawl that once housed Guy Fieri’s restaurant, Guy’s American Kitchen & Bar, has virtually the same menu. “The restaurant is really the same, even though there’s a different audience,” Bruce Bromberg said. “From the first Blue Ribbon in SoHo in 1992, our menus have had wide-ranging appeal.” Soups, smoked salmon, salads, burgers, a French dip, spit-roasted meats, pastas, steaks and prime ribs are served. There’s theatrical lighting throughout, from the ground-floor Marquee Bar, specializing in whiskeys, to the dining room, a space called the Oyster Bar, and other dining areas that can be used for à la carte dining or private parties. The décor is vintage New York, drawing largely from the 1920s to the ’40s, with old photographs, subtle references to The New York Times (which once occupied the building) and books from that era that are used to present the dinner check.  (Opens Wednesday)
